GradInit: optimizer hyperparameter enumeration and warmup no longer needed (by Google)

Google offered a super cool universal architecture-agnostic method for initializing model weights.

The idea is very simple: add multipliers before each block of parameters and run several iterations of loss optimization on them. Then we fix these multipliers and learn the model as usual. Such initialization does not depend on the depth and type of architecture (it works on both resnets and transformers) and almost completely solves the problem of exploding/fading gradients.

As a result, there is no need to enumerate the hyperparameters of the optimizer, and the transformer was generally trained without warmup, which was considered almost impossible. As a bonus, such initialization gives a small boost on many benchmarks (both picture and text).
